{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"6fdd8279-76ec-4b86-bf58-3ccfa272c0f4","content":"Use **`dotnet-trace`** — it's the lightest option that works well inside containers.\n\n### Steps\n\n**1. Install the tool inside the pod:**\n```bash\nkubectl exec -it <pod> -- bash\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\nexport PATH=\"$PATH:$HOME/.dotnet/tools\"\n```\n\n**2. Find your app's PID:**\n```bash\ndotnet-trace ps\n```\n\n**3. Collect a CPU profile (30s example):**\n```bash\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\nThis writes a `.nettrace` file you can analyze in **Visual Studio**, **PerfView**, or **Speedscope** (use `--format speedscope` for the latter).\n\n### Getting the file out\n```bash\nkubectl cp <pod>:/path/to/trace.nettrace ./trace.nettrace\n```\n\n### Tips\n- If `dotnet tool install` isn't viable (read-only filesystem), use the **standalone `dotnet-trace`** download instead:\n  ```bash\n  curl -sSL https://aka.ms/dotnet-trace/linux-x64 -o dotnet-trace\n  chmod +x dotnet-trace\n  ```\n- For deeper native + managed analysis, consider **`dotnet-stack report`** (snapshot) or **`perf`** (if available), but `dotnet-trace` is usually sufficient and easiest in containers.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"a66695ec-8a4b-4c57-9962-a30fe513a958","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app running in a Kubernetes pod on Linux. This is a diagnostics/troubleshooting question - I don't need to search any codebase, just provide expert guidance.","outputTokens":424,"requestId":"6008:1CA5E9:29822D:31341A:69EAC643"},"id":"b0677a46-c076-4c2d-aa7c-aee9da689478","timestamp":"2026-04-24T01:24:29.521Z","parentId":"9a9789d0-db45-4f5c-9a69-9dddb4fdf39b"}
